Capacity Expansion Objective
\[
\begin{align}
\min_{x, y, NSE} Z &= {\color{red}\text{investment cost} } + {\color{blue}\text{operating cost} } \\
&= {\color{red} \sum_{g \in \mathcal{G}} \text{FixedCost}_g x_g} + {\color{blue} \sum_{t \in \mathcal{T}} \sum_{g \in \mathcal{G}}  \text{VarCost}_g y_{g,t} + \sum_{t \in \mathcal{T}} \text{NSECost} NSE_t}
\end{align}
\]

Problem Formulation
\[
\begin{align}
\min_{x, y, NSE} \quad & \sum_{g \in \mathcal{G}} \text{FixedCost}_g x_g + \sum_{t \in \mathcal{T}} \sum_{g \in \mathcal{G}} \text{VarCost}_gy_{g,t} & \\
& \quad + \sum_{t \in \mathcal{T}} \text{NSECost} NSE_t & \\[0.5em]
\text {subject to:} \quad & \sum_{g \in \mathcal{G}} y_{g,t} + NSE_t = d_t & \forall t \in \mathcal{T} \\[0.5em]
& y_{g,t} \leq x_g & \forall g \in {G},  \forall t \in \mathcal{T} \\[0.5em]
& x_g, y_{g,t}, NSE_t \geq 0 & \forall g \in {G},  \forall t \in \mathcal{T}
\end{align}
\]

Box Models and Simulation
Many simulation models are built by:

Dividing the domain into individual boxes (1-D, 2-D, or 3-D);
Starting from initial box:

Simulate change to stock within box;
Obtain outflow as inflow into adjacent boxes;
Move onto next box;

If needed (e.g. non-steady-state), repeat for each time step.

Non-Steady State Solution
\[\begin{gather}
&\dot{m} = \frac{d(CV)}{dt} = \overbrace{(u WH) C_\text{in}}^{\text{inflow}} - \overbrace{(u WH) C}^{\text{outflow}} + \overbrace{S - D}^{\text{net emissions}} - \overbrace{kCV}^{\text{mass decay}} \\[0.5em]
&\class{fragment}{{} \frac{dC}{dt} = \underbrace{\frac{u WH}{V} C_\text{in} + \frac{S - D}{V}}_{\Large =P} - \underbrace{\left(\frac{u WH}{V} + k\right)}_{\Large =l} C} \\[0.5em]
&\class{fragment}{{} \frac{dC}{dt} = P - l C}
\end{gather}\]

Modeling Flows
For example:


Mass balance equations let us track changes in stocks at particular points;
Equilibrium conditions are requirements that there is no net flow, and thus that stocks are preserved;
Fate and transport modeling involves quantifying how stocks change as they move through the system.

